Price per year

First, lets look at the average cost of LEGO sets over time. The main variable of interest here is USD_MSRP, or the manufacturers suggested retail price in constant dollars (i.e.not adjusted for inflation).

Require data wrangling to see price per year

cmd-shift-m: shortcut for pipe operator %>%

legosets=legosets %>% mutate(duplo=ifelse(Theme %in% c("Duplo"), 1, 0))
# Overall mean cost
mean_cost=mean(legosets$USD_MSRP, na.rm = TRUE)

mean_cost
## [1] 27.89681
# Mean cost by year
## First drop missing values
## Group by: calculating per variable

avg_price_per_yr=legosets %>% 
  drop_na(USD_MSRP) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(
   count=n(),
   sum=sum(USD_MSRP),
   mean_price_per_yr=mean(USD_MSRP)
  )

avg_price_per_yr
## # A tibble: 45 x 4
##     Year count   sum mean_price_per_yr

##  8  1978     8  86.2             10.8

# Visualizing: scatterplot
## aes: specify mappings: takes information in the data, columns(variables), and renders them into aesthetic attributes 
## Inheritance: from base layer: data and aes but non-mapping will not be inheritated (e.g. size, colo, etc. )

## USD variable is not adjusted for inflation


ggplot(avg_price_per_yr, aes(Year,  mean_price_per_yr))+
  geom_line(color="purple", size=0.5)+
  geom_point(color="blue", size=0.5)+
  geom_smooth()+
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y= "Mean Price Per Year (USD)",
    title="Average Price of Lego Sets ",
    subtitle="Amounts are reported in current USD",
    caption="Source: LEGO"
  )+theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'



Pieces per year

Next, lets look at how the number of pieces per set has changed over time. Because Duplo sets are much smaller (since theyre designed for toddlers), well make a special indicator variable for them.

# Overall mean pieces
mean_pieces=mean(legosets$Pieces, na.rm = TRUE)

mean_pieces
## [1] 215.1686
# Mean pieces by year

avg_pieces_per_yr=legosets %>% 
  drop_na(Pieces) %>%
  group_by(Year, duplo) %>%
  summarise(
   num_sets=n(),
   sum=sum(Pieces),
   mean_ps_per_yr=mean(Pieces)
  )

avg_pieces_per_yr

There are 115 distinct themes.

theme_counts=legosets %>% 
  count(Theme, sort=TRUE) %>%
  # fct_inorder: turns chr into fct -- meaning a categorical variable
  mutate(Theme=fct_inorder(Theme, ordered=TRUE))


theme_counts %>% 
  filter(n>150, Theme != "Duplo") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=fct_rev(Theme), y=n))+
  # Not use geom_bar as it calculates the total for us
  # Since we have already calculated the totals for each them use geom_col
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()+
  labs(x=NULL, y="Number of Sets")+
  theme_minimal()

Class Notes

Types of Variables

Categorical/Factor; Continuous/Numeric

Two Questions to Ask Before Deciding the Graphics:

  1. How many variables? Uivariate or multivariate?

  2. Type of variable(s)?

When and why we use a ?

  1. Histogram:

  1. cts/numerical, can be discrete but cts works better

  2. univariate

  1. Boxplot: 5 summary of the data: min, 0.25 Percentile (first quadrat), Median (second quadrat), 0.75 Percentile (third quadrat), max

  1. cts/numerical

  2. univarite

  1. Bar plot (or called frequency plot): how frequent does the category/factor level show up (measured by the height of the bar)

  1. categorical/factor

  2. univariate

  3. Histogram and bar plot are for different types of variables:

  1. Histogram: for cts variable, usually does not have spaces in between bars

  2. Bar plot: for categorical variable, usually has spaces in between bars

  1. Scatterplot: shows relathips between two numerical variables

  1. cts/numerical

  2. bivariate

  1. Segmented/Stacked Bar Plot: shading categories within a bar (another categorical var)

  1. categorical by categorical

  2. bivariate

  1. Side-by-Side/Grouped Boxplot: boxplots for multiple groups so we can compare

  1. cts/numerical by categorical

  2. bivariate

We are able to take the above basic graphics and add additional aesthetics (i.e.information) and turn them to more than bivariate graphics (e.g.multivariate, showing relationships among more than 2 variables)
